1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,500
Elena | Coach: Let's start with a quick check-in. How is everyone feeling about the sprint we just closed?

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,200
David: Relieved, honestly. We shipped the payment flow but I think we took on too much and it showed in the last two days.

3
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:27,400
Priya: Agreed. We had three blockers that weren't flagged until Wednesday. I think our estimation process needs work.

4
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,600
Elena | Coach: What's one thing that would have made the sprint go smoother if you'd done it on day one?

5
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:47,800
David: A clearer definition of done for the payment ticket. We had three different interpretations across the team.

6
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:58,000
Priya: And earlier dependency mapping. We didn't know we were blocked on the backend team until it was already urgent.

7
00:00:58,600 --> 00:01:08,200
Elena | Coach: So definition of done and dependency mapping upfront. Are those things you can add to your sprint kick-off checklist?

8
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:18,400
David: Yes, I can own creating that checklist by end of this week.

9
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:28,600
Priya: And I'll set up a short dependency review slot at the start of every sprint — thirty minutes max.

10
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:38,800
Elena | Coach: Great. Let's revisit both in two weeks and see if they made a difference. What's the team's energy level going into this next sprint?

11
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:48,000
David: Better now that we've talked. I think we just needed to name the problems out loud.

12
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:55,000
Elena | Coach: That's exactly what retrospectives are for. Good work today, both of you.
